Exercice 1: bar chart & color palette

Question: reproduce this plot, based on the uspopchange dataframe.

To do that, you may want to have a look at

  1. this list of color palette, that you can use in combination to scale_fill_brewer()
  2. the labs() function

Do not forget to re-order the data so that the plot features this nice monotonic shape

ggplot(data = uspopchange) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=reorder(Abb, Change), y=Change, fill=Region), stat="identity", colour="black") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Pastel2") +
  labs(x = "State", y = "Population change") + 
  coord_flip()

Exercice 2: overlapping data points

Have a look at this graph, which plots hwy against cty, and compare it to the dimension of the mpg dataframe.

ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, hwy)) + geom_point() 

dim(mpg)
## [1] 234  11

The original data has 234 data points, but the chart seems to display fewer points. Why? There are overlapping points appearing as a single dot, since both cty and hwy are integers.

Question: find two ways to show the actual number of data points in the plot.

Hint:

  1. the solutions are already coded in two different geoms, you just have to find which ones
  2. to solve the problem, you may want to add noise (\(\approx\) jitter the data points) and / or to count the number of overlapping data points
# default plot
g <- ggplot(mpg, aes(cty, hwy))
# add some noise in the data points to visualize all of them 
g + geom_jitter(width = .5, size=1)

# increase the size of the marker based on how many data points overlap 
g + geom_count(show.legend=F)

Exercice 3: histograms & density plots

We would like to see the distribution of city mileage (cyl in the mpg dataframe), distinguishing the vehicles cylinders.

First, do that with a plain histogram.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = cty, fill = factor(cyl)), alpha = 0.8, color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Histograms", 
       subtitle="City Mileage Grouped by Number of cylinders",
       x="City Mileage",
       fill="# Cylinders")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

But the result is quite disappointing. In particular, we cannot see how these histograms overlap.

To solve this problem, we are going to use kernel density estimate (you are going to learn about that in Econometrics III), which are nothing but smoothed versions of histograms. Plot the distribution of city mileage by vehicles cylinders using these density plots.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_density(aes(x = cty, fill = factor(cyl)), alpha = 0.8, color = "black") + 
  labs( title = "Density plot", 
        subtitle="City Mileage Grouped by Number of cylinders",
        x="City Mileage",
        fill="# Cylinders")

Exercice 4: time series

Question: reproduce this plot, based on the climate data, collected by Berkeley. The shaded area represents the uncertainty for 10-year-smoothed anomaly.

Hint:

  1. you can obtain info on this dataset here
  2. start by subsetting the data set to focus only the data collected by Berkeley
  3. both the time series and the shaded area are already encoded in geoms
  4. the time series is a line
  5. the shaded area is a ribbon
ggplot(data = subset(climate, Source == "Berkeley"), mapping = aes(x=Year, y=Anomaly10y)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=Anomaly10y-Unc10y, ymax=Anomaly10y+Unc10y), alpha=0.2, fill = "tomato3", show.legend = TRUE) + 
  labs( title = "Time series", 
        y = "Temperature anomaly (C)",
        subtitle="Temperature anomaly in Celcius, smoothed over ten years")
